[[File:Boka Falls Slovenia.JPG|thumb|right|250px |Boka Falls]] '''Boka''' is a waterfall in the western part of Slovenia, near the [[Soča]] River. It begins at a [[karst]] spring and has two stages, of which the first is {{convert|106|m|sp=us}} high<ref name="KunaverES">{{cite encyclopedia|author=Kunaver, Jurij|url= |title=Boka|work=[[Enciklopedija Slovenije]] |volume=1 (A-Ca) | publisher=Mladinska knjiga| location=Ljubljana | date=1987 |pages=314–315 |isbn= | access-date= }} {{OCLC|468393318}} {{COBISS|ID=17411}} {{ISBN|86-11-14288-8}}</ref><ref>Skoberne, Peter. 1997. "Slap." ''Encliklopedija Slovenije'', vol. 11, pp. 123–124. Ljubljana: Mladinska knjiga, p. 124.</ref><ref name="RoughGuideSlovenia" /> and {{convert|18|m|sp=us}} wide, and the second is {{convert|33|m|sp=us}} high.<ref name="KunaverES" />
== Overview == The waterfall is supplied by a [[karst spring]]<ref name="KunaverES" /><ref>Kunaver, Jurij. 1990. "Kanin." ''Encliklopedija Slovenije'', vol. 4, pp. 395–396. Ljubljana: Mladinska knjiga, p. 396.</ref> under an almost vertical [[limestone]] wall. Because of its karst nature, the spring has a relatively large discharge due to its underground drainage in the mountains of [[Kanin Mountains|Kanin]]. During the driest periods, water flux is around {{convert|2|m3/s|sp=us}}, and reaches up to {{convert|100|m3/s|sp=us}} after extensive rains.<ref name="KunaverES" /> The stream (also called Boka) flows for about {{convert|30|m|sp=us}} over a rocky shelf before falling over the rocks as a spectacular waterfall. This happens in two not so clearly separated stages, of which the upper one has a height of {{convert|106|m|sp=us}}, and the lower one {{convert|33|m|sp=us}}.<ref name="KunaverES" /> The width of the two stages is around {{convert|18|m|sp=us}}.
Below the waterfall, Boka Creek flows over a steep valley with stony bottom and empties into the [[Soča]] River after less than {{convert|1|km|sp=us}}, which makes it one of the shortest streams in [[Slovenia]].
== Access == The waterfall is located on the right bank of the Soča River, about {{convert|1.3|km|sp=us}} from the river. The starting point to visit the waterfall is on the regional road between [[Kobarid]] and [[Bovec]], about {{convert|2.2|km|sp=us}} upstream from the village of [[Žaga, Bovec|Žaga]] or {{convert|6.1|km|sp=us}} downstream from the town of [[Bovec]]. The waterfall is visible from this road, especially its upper part. Next to the road and Boka Creek, there is a parking lot, and a gravel road leads uphill towards the waterfall. After about {{convert|100|m|sp=us}}, this road splits into path over the stream on the left, which transitions to a secured climbing path leading to the source of the waterfall, and into the path on the right that leads to the waterfall.<ref name="RoughGuideSlovenia">{{cite book | author=Rough Guides | url=https://books.google.lu/books?id=YNlLDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT187&dq=Boka&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=snippet&q=Boka&f=false | title=The Rough Guide to Slovenia | pages=142 | work= | publisher=Rough Guides UK | date=Jun 1, 2017 | isbn= | archive-url=https://archive.is/20170722113721/https://books.google.lu/books?id=YNlLDgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover%23v=onepage&q=Boka&f=false#v=snippet&q=Boka&f=false | archive-date=2017-07-22 | access-date=2017-07-05 | deadurl=yes | df= }}</ref><ref name="StewartSlovenia">{{cite book | author=James Stewart | url=https://books.google.lu/books?id=qwBUkHaz76QC | title=Slovenia | pages=110 | work=Cadogan Guides | publisher=New Holland Publishers | date=2006 | isbn= | archive-url=https://archive.is/20170722114545/https://books.google.lu/books?id=qwBUkHaz76QC&q=boka%23v=snippet&q=boka&f=false | archive-date=2017-07-22 | access-date=2017-07-05 | deadurl=yes | df= }}</ref>
