{{distinguish|Vehicle tracking system}}
'''Vehicle location data''' is the [[big data]] collection of [[vehicle]] locations, including [[automatic vehicle location]] data. This usually includes times and often photographs as well.<ref name=wsjonline1>{{cite news |url = https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10000872396390443995604578004723603576296 |title = New Tracking Frontier: Your License Plates |author1= [[Julia Angwin]] |last2 = Valentino-DeVries |first2 = Jennifer |date = 29 September 2012 |website = online.wsj.com |publisher = [[Wall Street Journal]] |accessdate = 14 July 2013 }}</ref> <ref name=cir1>{{cite web |url = http://cironline.org/reports/license-plate-readers-let-police-collect-millions-records-drivers-4883 |title = License-plate readers let police collect millions of records on drivers |last = Winston |first = Ali |date = 26 June 2013 |website = cironline.org |publisher = [[Center for Investigative Reporting]] |accessdate = 19 July 2013 }}</ref> Common methods of data collection include [[automatic number plate recognition]] of [[vehicle registration plate]]s from images collected by cameras mounted on vehicles or fixtures along roads, <ref name=wsjonline1 /> <ref name=cir1 /> <ref name=guardian1>{{cite news |url = https://www.theguardian.com/law/2013/jul/17/million-american-license-plate-privacy-tracking |title = Millions of US license plates tracked and stored, new ACLU report finds |last = Pilkington |first = Ed |date = 17 July 2013 |website = guardian.co.uk |publisher = [[The Guardian]] |accessdate = 17 July 2013 |location=London }}</ref> <ref name=nbcnews1>{{cite web |url = http://investigations.nbcnews.com/_news/2013/07/19/19548772-license-plate-data-not-just-for-cops-private-companies-are-tracking-your-car |title = License plate data not just for cops: Private companies are tracking your car |last = Aegerter |first = Gil |date = 19 July 2013 |website = investigations.nbcnews.com |publisher = [[NBC News]] |accessdate = 19 July 2013 }}</ref> as well as [[radio-frequency identification]] (RFID) from [[dedicated short-range communications]] transponders<ref name=brooklyn1>{{cite web |url = http://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/36/19/all_ezpassbigbrother_2013_05_10_bk.html |title = Big Brother has it ‘E-Z’: City now tracking cars through local streets thanks to E-ZPass |last = Lutz |first = Jaime |date = 8 May 2013 |website = www.brooklynpaper.com |publisher = The Brooklyn Paper |accessdate = 19 July 2013 }}</ref> <ref name=pcworld1> {{cite web |url = http://www.pcworld.com/article/199929/location_tracking_services_why_you_should_think_twice.html |title = Location-Tracking Services: Why You Should Think Twice |last = Tynan |first = Dan |date = |website = www.pcworld.com |publisher = [[PC World]] |accessdate = 19 July 2013 }}</ref> (such as those used for [[electronic toll collection]] and [[parking lot]]s). [[Database]]s of this information may be maintained by government or private entities. Private companies use vehicle location data for vehicle [[repossession]] and consumer profiling.<ref name=wsjonline1 /> Government databases have been subjected to legal orders for location data.<ref name=pcworld1 /><ref name=usatoday1>{{cite news |url = http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/nation/2007-08-12-ez-pass_N.htm |title = Adultery has a new monitor: E-ZPass |last = Newmarker |first = Chris |date = 10 August 2007 |website = usatoday.com |publisher = [[USA Today]] |accessdate = 25 July 2013 }}</ref> Access may be restricted to use in criminal cases, but may also be available for civil cases, such as divorce.<ref name=usatoday1 />
==Automatic number plate recognition== {{main|Automatic number plate recognition}}
[[Vehicle registration plate]]s may be automatically scanned with equipment, mountable on vehicles, that identifies an image characteristic of a registration plates, takes a photograph, and reads and records the registration number.<ref name=wsjonline1 /> Such scanning may be done by government <ref name=wsjonline1 /><ref name=cir1 /> or private industry.<ref name=wsjonline1 /><ref name=guardian1 /><ref name=nbcnews1 /> Private industry collects this information for profit through, directly or indirectly, activities such as consumer profiling and repossession.<ref name=wsjonline1 /><ref name=nbcnews1 /> Companies have collected over 1 billion scans of registration plates in the United States,<ref name=nbcnews1 /> stored in multiple [[National databases of United States persons|national databases]].
==Transponders== [[Radio-frequency identification]] (RFID) read from [[dedicated short-range communications|dedicated short-range communication]] transponders voluntarily obtained by citizens for [[electronic toll collection]] enable recording of time and location data at toll crossings.<ref name=usatoday1 /> Scanning equipment has also been installed at additional, non-toll locations,<ref name=forbes1>{{cite news |url = https://www.forbes.com/sites/kashmirhill/2013/09/12/e-zpasses-get-read-all-over-new-york-not-just-at-toll-booths/ |title = E-ZPasses Get Read All Over New York (Not Just At Toll Booths) |last = Hill |first = Kashmir |date = 12 September 2013 |website = forbes.com |publisher = [[Forbes]] |accessdate = 22 October 2013 }}</ref><ref name=brooklyn1 /> enabling further data collection. Transponders have also been hacked, allowing reading and tracking by unauthorized parties.<ref name=cnet1>{{cite web |url = http://news.cnet.com/8301-1009_3-10009353-83.html |title = Security expert explains how data can be stolen off electronic toll devices and how people can be tracked in real time |last = Mills |first = Elinor |date = 6 August 2008 |website = news.cnet.com |publisher = [[C-Net]] |accessdate = 25 July 2013 }}</ref> <ref name=traffictech1>{{cite web |url = http://www.traffictechnologytoday.com/news.php?NewsID=7366 |title = Toll road transponder security hacked |last = |first = |date = 13 August 2008 |website = www.traffictechnologytoday.com |publisher = Traffic Technology Today |accessdate = 25 July 2013 }}</ref> <ref name=rootlabs1>{{cite web |url = http://rdist.root.org/2008/08/07/fastrak-talk-summary-and-slides/ |title = FasTrak talk summary and slides |last = Lawson |first = Nate |date = 7 August 2008 |website = rdist.root.org |publisher = Root Labs |accessdate = 25 July 2013 }}</ref>
==Privacy concerns== The [[American Civil Liberties Union]] issued a report on license plate tracking, finding that the vast majority of scans collected are the vehicles of innocent persons.<ref name=aclu1>{{cite web |url = https://www.aclu.org/alpr |title = You Are Being Tracked: How License Plate Readers Are Being Used to Record Americans' Movements |last = |first = |date = |website = www.aclu.org |publisher = [[American Civil Liberties Union]] |accessdate = 19 July 2013 }}</ref> <ref name=guardian1 /> <ref name=nbcnews2>{{cite web |url = http://www.nbcnews.com/technology/aclu-digital-dragnet-ensnares-millions-innocent-drivers-6C10654018 |title = ACLU: Digital dragnet ensnares millions of innocent drivers |last = Sullivan |first = Bob |date = 17 July 2013 |website = www.nbcnews.com |publisher = [[NBC News]] |accessdate = 19 July 2013 }}</ref>
